          "body": "The birth narrative of vv. 24-26 is dense with name-etiology. Esau emerges red (*admoni*) and hairy like a garment — the physical description that will attach to him and his land (Edom, *adom*, red, v.30) for the rest of Scripture. Jacob emerges grasping Esau's heel (*aqev*), and his name *Yaaqov* encodes that gesture. The name can mean 'he grasps the heel' but also carries the connotation 'supplanter' — a word that Esau will use in bitter irony in 27:36. The characterization in vv. 27-28 sets the stage for the entire Jacob cycle: Esau is a man of the field, a skillful hunter, physically competent in the outer world; Jacob is a *tam* man — the Hebrew word means 'blameless,' 'whole,' 'peaceful,' but also 'plain,' 'simple.' It is the same word used of Noah (6:9) and Job (1:1). The parental favoritism of v.28 is named without apology: Isaac loved Esau for appetite-driven reasons (*ki tsayid bepio*, 'because game was in his mouth'); Rebekah loved Jacob. The division of the household along election-lines is already visible in the parents' affections."
