        "excerpt": "Now Abraham gave all that he had to Isaac; but to the sons of his concubines, Abraham gave gifts while he was still living, and sent them away from his son Isaac eastward.",
        "body": "The opening eleven verses perform a single theological action: they close the Abraham era by distributing his legacy in a way that makes unmistakably clear who the covenant heir is. Keturah's six sons and the sons of unnamed concubines receive gifts — the Hebrew *mattanah* (v.6) is a word for a voluntary, gracious donation, not an inheritance. The distinction between *mattanah* and the total estate (*kol-asher lo*, 'all that he had,' v.5) is legally precise. In patriarchal culture, the firstborn son received a double portion and the headship of the family; all others received defined allocations. Abraham exceeds legal obligation by giving the concubines' sons gifts, but he does not blur the covenant line. They are sent eastward — *qedemah*, toward the sunrise, which in Genesis's symbolic geography consistently marks movement away from the covenant land (cf. 4:16; 13:11; 11:2).\n\nAbraham's death at 175 is narrated with four interlocking phrases: 'breathed his last,' 'died in a ripe old age,' 'an old man and satisfied with life,' and 'was gathered to his people' (v.8). The phrase 'gathered to his people' (*ne'esaph el-ammav*) is distinct from burial — it implies reunion with those who have died before him, a pre-Mosaic intuition of post-mortem community (cf. the identical formula for Ishmael in v.17, and for Aaron in Numbers 20:24). Calvin notes that this expression implies a hope of resurrection, or at minimum a conviction that death is not annihilation (*Commentary on Genesis*, 1554).\n\nThe burial at Machpelah (vv. 9-10) is not incidental. Abraham purchased this cave from Ephron the Hittite in Genesis 23 specifically as a burial place for Sarah — it is the only land Abraham ever legally owned in Canaan. His burial there is his permanent staking of claim in the promised land before Israel has conquered a single city. Isaac and Ishmael bury him together (v.9) — a rare moment of sibling unity that the text records without comment, perhaps to show that even the most divided family can honor a common father.\n\nVerse 11 bridges the two eras with surgical brevity: 'After the death of Abraham, God blessed his son Isaac.' The covenant transfers without hesitation. God does not wait for Israel's grief to pass, or for the estate to be fully settled, or for Isaac to prove himself. The blessing continues, because the blessing is God's to give, not Abraham's.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mattanah* (gift, v.6) vs. *kol-asher lo* (all that he had, v.5) — the legal distinction is between inheritance and donation. *Ne'esaph el-ammav* (gathered to his people, vv. 8, 17) — the phrase appears 11 times in the Pentateuch; it is not merely a poetic synonym for death but implies a gathering to a prior community of the dead."
