        "body": "The Isaac toledot opens with the same crisis that opened the Abraham narrative: a barren wife. But where Sarah's barrenness extended over decades with no initial divine promise of remedy, Rebekah's barrenness is addressed immediately through prayer. Isaac *entreated* the LORD (*vaye'tar Yitschaq*, v.21), and the LORD *was entreated of him* (*vaye'ater lo*) — the same Hebrew root appears in both clauses, creating a verbal chiasm that makes the prayer-and-answer inseparable. God's response is not grudging or delayed; it mirrors the request in the same breath. This is one of the Old Testament's clearest patterns of intercessory prayer answered: a single verse contains the petition and the fulfillment.\n\nRebekah's inquiry (*darash*, v.22) when the twins struggle in her womb is theologically significant. *Darash* is the technical term for seeking a divine oracle — used later for consulting a prophet or inquiring at a sanctuary (cf. 1 Kings 22:5; 2 Kings 8:8). Rebekah does not simply complain; she goes to God for an interpretation of her experience. The LORD's answer in verse 23 is the chapter's theological center and one of the most programmatic statements in all of Genesis: two nations, two peoples, separation, strength differential, and — most strikingly — the reversal of birth order.\n\n'The older shall serve the younger' is not a prediction of individual servitude but a national oracle: Edom (descended from Esau) will serve Israel (descended from Jacob). This was fulfilled partially under David (2 Samuel 8:14) and more fully in the Maccabean period. But the NT reading is determinative: Paul quotes v.23 in Romans 9:11-12 as proof that God's election operates 'before the children had done anything good or bad.' The oracle is pre-natal, pre-moral, pre-meritorious — a declaration of divine purpose that cannot be earned or forfeited by human performance. Reformed and Arminian readers divide sharply here: the Reformed tradition (Calvin, Edwards, Moo) reads this as unconditional individual and corporate election; the classical Arminian tradition reads it as corporate election (the nation of Israel over the nation of Edom) without implying anything about the individuals' final salvation. Both readings are exegetically possible; the Romans 9 context must adjudicate.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Atar* (to entreat, to pray) — the root occurs in both the Qal and the Niphal in v.21, creating a call-and-response pattern: Isaac entreated / the LORD was entreated. *Darash* (to inquire, v.22) — technical term for divine consultation; stronger than casual questioning. *Rav / tsair* (older / younger, v.23) — literally 'great / small,' reinforcing the status reversal."
