        "body": "The birth narrative compresses years into four verses: the physical descriptions of Esau and Jacob at birth, the name-etiologies, and Isaac's age at their birth (60). Both descriptions are loaded with anticipation. Esau's redness (*admoni*, v.25) and hairiness are not neutral details — they anticipate the name Edom and the wordplay of v.30, tying the patriarch to the nation permanently. Jacob's grasping of Esau's heel (*aqev*, v.26) is the narrative's explanation for the name *Yaaqov*, which the broader Hebrew tradition hears as 'he who supplants' or 'the heel-grabber.' Hosea 12:3 reads the heel-grasping as evidence of Jacob's character from birth: 'In the womb he took his brother by the heel.' The birth is itself a character statement.\n\nThe vocational contrast of v.27 is the chapter's most economical character portrait. Esau is *yodea' tsayid ish sadeh* — 'a man knowing hunting, a man of the field.' His competence is in the external world: physical skill, outdoor provision, practical mastery. Jacob is *ish tam yoshev ohalim* — 'a man of integrity, dwelling in tents.' The word *tam* is the same word used for Noah ('blameless,' 6:9) and Job ('blameless,' 1:1, 1:8) — it is the word for moral wholeness, not perfection. But it is combined with *yoshev ohalim* (living in tents), which in the patriarchal world means domestic life, proximity to the camp, the world of the women and the household. Jacob is not effeminate; he is oriented toward the domestic and covenantal sphere rather than the wilderness.\n\nThe parental favoritism of v.28 is stated with clinical brevity. Isaac loved Esau *ki tsayid bepio* — 'because game was in his mouth,' literally 'because of the game in his mouth.' Isaac's love for his firstborn is appetite-driven: Esau brings him what he likes to eat. Rebekah's love for Jacob is not given a stated reason — perhaps because the oracle of v.23 is reason enough. The division of the household along the lines of the divine election is not coincidental; it is the story positioning itself for the deception of chapter 27, when Rebekah will exploit Isaac's appetite-love to transfer the blessing to Jacob.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tam* (blameless, whole, peaceful, v.27) — used of Noah (6:9), Job (1:1), and in Psalm 37:37 ('observe the blameless man'). Not moral perfection but moral wholeness, integrity. *Yoshev ohalim* (living in tents) — in the patriarchal world, 'tent' (*ohel*) is the space of the household, the women, the domestic covenant."
