        "excerpt": "Thus Esau despised his birthright.",
        "body": "The birthright transaction is one of the most carefully paced scenes in Genesis. Its economy of language is not carelessness; it is the narrator's way of showing how quickly and casually an inheritance of enormous spiritual weight can be bartered. Esau returns from the field 'famished' (*ayeph*, v.29) — exhausted and hungry, but not dying. His demand — 'Let me have a swallow of that red stuff there, for I am famished' — is remarkable for its crudeness. He does not ask for food by name; he points at the color. The text withholds 'lentil stew' until v.34, after the transaction is complete, as if to underscore that Esau did not even know exactly what he was trading his birthright for. He sold it for something he could not fully identify.\n\nJacob's counter-demand is immediate and calculated: 'First sell me your birthright' (v.31). The word *bekhorah* (birthright) enters the chapter here and appears four times in four verses — the concentrated repetition hammers the reader: this is what is at stake, this is what is being discussed, this is what Esau is trading away. The *bekhorah* in the patriarchal context carries the double inheritance (Deuteronomy 21:17), the right to lead the family after the father's death, and — in the Abrahamic narrative — the covenantal headship through which the blessing of 12:1-3 will pass. Esau's dismissal — 'I am about to die; so of what use then is the birthright to me?' (v.32) — is the chapter's diagnostic sentence. His reasoning inverts the proper relationship between present appetite and future covenantal standing: he argues that because he might die (from ordinary hunger, not from any mortal threat), the future is irrelevant. The man who cannot see beyond his stomach cannot value what does not gratify immediately.\n\nJacob insists on an oath (*shava*, v.33) — he wants the transfer to be legally binding, not retractable. Esau swears; Jacob gives him bread and lentil stew. Verse 34's six rapid verbs — 'ate and drank, and rose and went on his way' — compress the aftermath into an almost contemptuous sequence: for Esau, the transaction is already over. He ate, he left. The narrator then delivers the verdict: *bazah Esav et-habekhorah* — 'Esau despised his birthright.' The word *bazah* does not mean 'undervalued'; it means 'treated with contempt,' 'held in despite.' Hebrews 12:16 glosses this as *bebelos* — godless, profane, secular-minded, one who treats holy things as common. Jonathan Edwards, in *Religious Affections* (1746), uses Esau as the paradigmatic example of a person whose religious instincts are entirely driven by appetite rather than holy affection — one who has the form of covenantal position without the substance of covenantal devotion.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ayeph* (famished, exhausted, vv. 29-30) — the word for weariness from labor, not the word for starvation (*raev*). Esau uses hyperbole, not fact. *Bazah* (despised, v.34) — the same verb used in 1 Samuel 2:30 ('those who despise Me will be lightly esteemed') and Malachi 1:6 (Israel despising God's name). The narrator's use of *bazah* is a theological verdict, not merely a psychological one."
